<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="17" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/10428</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                President <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-03">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 3, 1916</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: Enclosed is a most
                            confidential message just received from Gerard.<note n="8a" xml:id="d17fn1">
                                <ref target="frus1916#pg_27">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, supp., p.
                                    27</ref>.</note> I am a little puzzled as to the real purpose of
                            introducing the subject at the present time. It would look to me like an
                            attempted diversion on Germany’s part in order to create here a
                            sympathetic feeling which would prevent radical action on our part. Of
                            course I may be in error as to the motive of the German official who
                            undoubtedly inspired this telegram but I confess to be very skeptical as
                            to the <hi rend="italic">bona fides</hi> of the suggestion.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>